<subSubSection id="541CFDF3637237990A34313ED0946A36" pageId="null" pageNumber="711" type="vernacular_names">
<paragraph id="EB15292403222FB1DBEFA9E192146C93" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Teppich-Johanniskraut</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</title>
<subSubSection id="6B24BDBCA7DDEDFABE41562794B1DBB0" pageId="null" pageNumber="711" type="description">
<paragraph id="8607FB43231DA86DA0CCF983276C9DA0" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">
Bis 30 cm hoch, am Grunde verholzt; ganze Pflanze ohne 
<normalizedToken id="A17A784DDB4C7E13488F5DD55880D732" originalValue="Drüsen" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Druesen</normalizedToken>
. Stengel zahlreich, bogig aufsteigend, meist 4kantig. 
<normalizedToken id="C080DE7964B4E0F5B6D0F6F246F72FB5" originalValue="Blätter" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Blaetter</normalizedToken>
oval, 5-10 cm lang, 2-3mal so lang wie breit, 
<emphasis id="0232E2BE69F2AEB2ABB651918E3A1523" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">
<normalizedToken id="D832C1EB8B3F475B1F54F1BD6C795990" originalValue="immergrün" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">immergruen</normalizedToken>
</emphasis>
(in milden Wintern). 
<emphasis id="7237E371C8E5769A5B3A02F6C6100AF3" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">
<normalizedToken id="5F53A6E062BFCF47D5CE828F9139B688" originalValue="Blüten" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Blueten</normalizedToken>
einzeln.
</emphasis>
<normalizedToken id="10E2CAB6D3A62DE70FFD5B0C86A16171" originalValue="Kelchblätter" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Kelchblaetter</normalizedToken>
oval, ungleich 
<normalizedToken id="BE4B4D68B50D72C17D053D792CCB6062" originalValue="groß" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">gross</normalizedToken>
, 10-20 mm lang, etwa 2mal so lang wie breit. 
<emphasis id="23FD23C0E446287DEB70E4077546E05C" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">
<normalizedToken id="BB53A1F03829B880FD78CF652C2262E7" originalValue="Kronblätter" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Kronblaetter</normalizedToken>
sehr 
<normalizedToken id="5443FF0A73170277FE727EA66B32A83A" originalValue="groß" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">gross</normalizedToken>
, 3-4 cm lang
</emphasis>
(bei den andern Arten des Gebiets nicht 
<normalizedToken id="6D0DECAFE294A8BCC9F697A61BFC823F" originalValue="über" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">ueber</normalizedToken>
2 cm lang), abfallend. 
<emphasis id="3F4BD71C4AF4279888E2743C546BD378" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">
<normalizedToken id="3D0C040152C7D97EBF6E0EB403A48D11" originalValue="Staubblätter" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Staubblaetter</normalizedToken>
am Grunde in 5 
<normalizedToken id="A3ED70B19F1D5EC686EB5659F58FD7C8" originalValue="Bündel" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Buendel</normalizedToken>
verwachsen
</emphasis>
(im Gebiet sonst nur bei 
<emphasis id="DF5002A236B37B84D4F08B08ACFEB361" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">
H. 
<taxonomicName id="AE1D57488FA7628560FE5D19F57240C9" authority="Nr." authorityName="Nr." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Hypericaceae" genus="Androsaemum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="null" pageNumber="711" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Androsaemum Nr.</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
2 und 
<taxonomicName id="63BC42CAE05C909210E7351856F69B3A" authority="Nr." authorityName="Nr." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Hypericaceae" genus="Hypericum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="null" pageNumber="711" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hircinum">
<emphasis id="272FD712E981CF73D3823513C78F9CEA" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">H. hircinum</emphasis>
Nr.
</taxonomicName>
3 so!). 
<emphasis id="C6749F36748BB45F787C3B7E0F332C19" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Griffel 5</emphasis>
(bei den andern Arten des Gebiets 3 Griffel!), viel 
<normalizedToken id="8F9B954A2F08F1D1633B6DF2544CB59B" originalValue="länger" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">laenger</normalizedToken>
als der Fruchtknoten, aufrecht. 
<emphasis id="A43D3B08608C20F3EE3D9842302D4A1B" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Fruchtkapsel nickend</emphasis>
(im Gebiet nur bei dieser Art so!). - 
<normalizedToken id="673227EA36373B07F35EFAB07C146BBF" originalValue="Blüte" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Bluete</normalizedToken>
: Sommer und Herbst.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F7C751970405D79334E8F841C089F9EE" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">
<emphasis id="28C04DCCE966682E52627470D242D159" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Zytologische Angaben. 2n</emphasis>
= 
<emphasis id="04EFCF1CBBDD17308B7895C3B0D6A688" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">20:</emphasis>
Material aus botanischen 
<normalizedToken id="BE2CA82AF799A2A6D27D11052CE6598C" originalValue="Gärten" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Gaerten</normalizedToken>
(Chattaway 1926; Robson und Adams 1968).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D6F4B345BB40895697581728349381A3" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">
<emphasis id="72031681817123A242DA7E11E65337D7" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Standort.</emphasis>
Kollin und montan. Warme Lagen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F6A17EAF5FACCEA391D7C2C8B39037FC" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">
<emphasis id="A38115DD0FA023C6DE7F11D9ED8F478F" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Verbreitung.</emphasis>
<normalizedToken id="3D6A2C3BED1653C1EDC898E710A17252" originalValue="Ursprünglich" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Urspruenglich</normalizedToken>
<emphasis id="C203C4845FFA1FBC05ED02A9028B14AC" italics="true" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">
<normalizedToken id="EA7C7753DF2997E3EA5824DD42A5DC31" originalValue="südosteuropäisch-westasiatische" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">suedosteuropaeisch-westasiatische</normalizedToken>
Pflanze:
</emphasis>
Griechenland (Thrakien), 
<normalizedToken id="54F46B07D61CBADAD86F95EFBB34DECD" originalValue="Küstengebiete" pageId="null" pageNumber="711">Kuestengebiete</normalizedToken>
des schwarzen Meeres, Kaukasus, Nordpersien. - Im Gebiet seit der Mitte des 17. Jahrhunderts als Gartenpflanze bekannt; selten verwildert.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
